#To add service and timer to the Systemd service
1) Copy the dosimeter_read.service and dosimeter_read.timer to /etc/systemd/system directory

Terminal Command: cp dosimeter_read.service dosimeter_read.timer /etc/systemd/system

2) Reload the systemd service modules

Terminal Command: sudo systemctl daemon-reload

3) Enable the systemd timer module (timer module is disabled by default)

Terminal Command: sudo systemctl enable dosimeter_read.timer

4) Start the systemd timer module (Once the timer module is enabled, we need to start it, it is stopped by default)

Terminal Command: sudo systemctl start dosimeter_read.timer

5) Check the status of the dosimeter_read.service to see whether it executes successfully or encounters a failure

Terminal Command: sudo systemctl status dosimeter_read.service

Normally, if it executes without an error, you will see a Green Light next to dosimeter_read.timer (status=0/SUCCESS), and it tells you when was the last executed time (XXs ago)

#To stop and disable the scheduled service

1) First, the timer service should be stopped first. The command below will stop the timer so the service will no longer be triggered. 

Terminal Command: sudo systemctl stop dosimeter_read.timer

Note that the timer is stopped in this session, but if the device reboots, the timer will start again.

2) To completely disable the timer service, the command below will disable the timer altogether

Terminal Command: sudo systemctl disable dosimeter_read.timer

